Acrocomia totai

   [2787.jpg]
   Authority C. Martius
   Family Liliopsida:Arecidae:Arecales:Palmae
   Synonyms
   Common names total, palma de vino, mocaya, cayiete, ocori, gru gru,
   grau, mukalla, uba, mujuca, noz de Paraguai
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 2787

   Notes
   (06.06.03) E2787
   DESCRIPTION: Evergreen palm reaching 13-20 m in height. Some specimens
   bear numerous large, black spines on the trunk, petioles and leaves.
   USE: Nut eaten roasted. A liquor is made from the fermentation of the
   sweet pulp. The trunk contains a starchy substance used to make bread
   and cakes. The heart can be used as palmito. The macerated leaves are
   used to make ropes. The oil is used for food and soaps. It is a good
   roadside palm. GROWING PERIOD: Perennial. COMMON NAMES: Total, Palma de
   vino. FURTHER INF: Present in sandy soils of lowlands (pampas) of the
   north of Argentina and also in eastern Bolivia, south-western Brazil,
   north-eastern Paraguay. In the United States it is only found in
   Florida. Is the most cold resistant of all Acrocomias, tolerating frost
   without damage.

   Sources
   Eeckenbrugge and Ferla 2000 (Acrocomia totai)

